# ============================================================
# Modelfile for devstral-small-2 — M5 Pro, 48GB, coding agent
# Covers both Zed agent and Claude Code usage (single config)
# Build: ollama create devstral-coder -f Modelfile
# ============================================================

# Devstral Small 2 — 24B dense params, 256K context, Q4_K_M.
# Fits comfortably in ~14GB of unified memory on your 48GB M5 Pro.
FROM devstral-small-2

# ── Sampling parameters ─────────────────────────────────────

# Mistral officially recommends 0.15 for Devstral 2 in agentic
# use (lower than general chat models). Very low temperature
# keeps tool calls and code edits deterministic. Slightly
# raised to 0.2 here to avoid degenerate repetition on long
# file outputs — still well within the deterministic range.
PARAMETER temperature 0.2

# top_p: nucleus sampling cutoff. 0.95 is Mistral's default
# for this model family and works well at low temperature.
PARAMETER top_p 0.95

# top_k: candidate token pool at each step. 20 is Mistral's
# recommended value for Devstral — intentionally tight to
# reinforce deterministic code generation.
PARAMETER top_k 20

# Mild repetition penalty. Code legitimately repeats patterns
# (variable names, loop constructs) so keep this low. 1.05
# discourages only true pathological loops without interfering
# with normal code structure.
PARAMETER repeat_penalty 1.05

# Disable presence penalty entirely — same reasoning as above.
# Penalising token presence hurts identifier reuse in code.
PARAMETER presence_penalty 0.0

# ── Context window ──────────────────────────────────────────

# Devstral Small 2 supports 256K context natively. With your
# OLLAMA_KV_CACHE_TYPE=q8_0 and 48GB unified memory, 65536 is
# a safe ceiling that accommodates large multi-file agent
# sessions without memory pressure. The model fits in ~14GB,
# leaving ~30GB headroom; q8_0 KV cache at 65536 tokens costs
# roughly 8-10GB for a 24B dense model.
# Raise to 131072 cautiously if you need full repo context,
# but watch Activity Monitor for memory pressure warnings.
PARAMETER num_ctx 32768

# Batch size for prompt ingestion (prefill). 512 is the sweet
# spot for Apple Silicon — large enough to parallelise long
# prompt evaluation, conservative enough to avoid memory spikes
# on the initial context load of a big codebase.
PARAMETER num_batch 512

# ── Hardware ────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Force all layers onto the GPU via Metal. On Apple Silicon,
# CPU and GPU share unified memory so there's no transfer
# overhead — everything runs on-chip at full bandwidth.
PARAMETER num_gpu 999

# M5 Pro has 6 "super cores" (high single-thread) + 12 "performance cores"
# (efficient multithreaded). 10 threads targets all super cores plus 4
# performance cores, leaving headroom for Zed and the OS.
PARAMETER num_thread 10

# No cap on generated tokens — let the model complete full
# file edits and multi-step tool call chains uninterrupted.
PARAMETER num_predict -1

# ── System prompt ───────────────────────────────────────────

# Note: when using Claude Code via `ollama launch claude`,
# Claude Code injects its own system prompt at runtime and
# this SYSTEM block is effectively overridden. It still
# applies for direct Zed agent usage and ollama run sessions.
#
# Derived from Mistral's recommended OpenHands-style prompt,
# trimmed for general coding agent use without scaffold
# assumptions.
SYSTEM """You are Devstral, an expert software engineering assistant built by Mistral AI. You help users write, edit, debug, and reason about code.

- You are thorough and methodical; prioritise correctness over speed.
- When editing existing code, preserve the author's conventions and style.
- If a request is ambiguous, ask for clarification before proceeding.
- If the user asks a question (e.g. "why is X happening"), answer it directly — do not silently attempt a fix.
- Prefer explicit, readable solutions. Briefly explain trade-offs when multiple approaches exist.
- Always include necessary imports and handle errors appropriately.
- For shell commands, prefer macOS/Unix idioms.
- You can read images but cannot generate them."""
